#: ../twitter-integration.rst:26
msgid ""
"As of June 2013, Twitter also requires that all API access is authenticated."
" For this you'll need to configure a Twitter application with OAuth "
"credentials for your site to access the Twitter API. These credentials are "
"configurable as Mezzanine settings. See the :doc:`configuration` section for"
" more information on these, as well as the `Twitter developer site "
"<https://dev.twitter.com/>`_ for info on creating an application and "
"configuring your OAuth credentials."
msgstr ""

#: ../twitter-integration.rst:36
msgid "Sending Tweets"
msgstr ""

#: ../twitter-integration.rst:38
msgid ""
"When setting up a Twitter application, you'll also be able to configure the "
"permissions your OAuth credentials have against the Twitter API. To consume "
"Twitter feeds, only read permissions are needed, but you may also choose to "
"allow both read and write permissions. With write permissions enabled, "
"you'll then also be able to expose the option in Mezzanine's admin interface"
" for automatically tweeting new blog posts (or your own custom content) when"
" they're published."
msgstr ""

#: ../twitter-integration.rst:46
msgid ""
"To enable this, simply install the `python-twitter "
"<https://pypi.python.org/pypi/python-twitter>` library. With the library "
"installed and credential setttings set, blog posts in the admin will have a "
"\"Send to Twitter\" checkbox, which when checked, will send a tweet with the"
" post's title and URL."
msgstr ""

#: ../twitter-integration.rst:52
msgid ""
"You can also add this functionality to your own admin classes by making use "
"of ``mezzanine.twitter.admin.TweetableAdminMixin``. See "
"``mezzanine.blog.admin.BlogPostAdmin`` for an example."
msgstr ""
